{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-802c9ce8c4702d5a", "type": "tool_result", "content": " ] . Natural conversation therefore requires not only intelligible speech, but also appropriate timing and turn-taking [ 8 ] : late responses may feel slow, while early responses may interrupt the user, especially in full-duplex systems that must decide when to answer while speech is still arriving [ 36 , 4 ] . Standard metrics such as WER and UTMOS [ 34 ] remain useful, but do not fully capture these interactional dimensions: a model can have low WER and high speech quality while answering at the wrong time, using a flat voice, missing the emotion of the question, or changing the interpersonal stance. Recent work has demonstrated that evaluator models can be used to reliably estimate conversation-level properties, including turn-taking naturalness with Voice Activity Prediction models [ 52 ] , emotional naturalness and entrainment [ 41 ] , interpersonal stance [ 45 ] , and dialect profiles across languages [ 15 ] . SPEARBench leverages these models in Section III-C . II-C Existing Benchmarks for Speech-to-Speech Language Models Evaluation Many benchmarks evaluate speech processing models and LLMs. Some focus on speech understanding tasks such as transcription, spoken question answering, speech translation, or audio reasoning, including SUPERB-style benchmarks for speech foundation models [ 51 ] . Others compare LLM abilities in text-only [ 24 , 7 ] or speech-based settings [ 50 , 53 , 38 ] . These benchmarks measure important capabilities, but they often focus on isolated utterances or task correctness rather than conversational behavior, leading to known gaps and inconsistencies across evaluations [ 23 ] . Recent work has begun evaluating full-duplex spoken interaction, including emergency scenarios [ 17 ] , latency [ 32 ] , interruptions [ 25 ] , and turn efficiency [ 17 ] . Some commercial initiatives, such as Artificial Analysis [ 5 ] , provide scores for AI agents that include automatic evaluation of pause handling, turn-taking, interruption handling, and backchannel handling, but they do not provide an open-source benchmark with peer-reviewed reports or articles. Other initiatives, such as Speech Arena [ 37 ] or Voice Arena [ 42 ] are more focused on text-to-speech systems rather than AI agents and mainly use human evaluations to create their leaderboards. Consequently, most benchmarks still focus on a single dimension, are not open, or require human intervention. SPEARBench complements them by providing an open-source automated benchmark for conversational naturalness on a wide set of aspects. Figure 1 : SPEARBench pipeline. III Methods This section details the proposed benchmark implementation, which consists of three steps: data preparation, LLM inference for each S2S model evaluated, and then evaluation. Figure 1 summarizes the pipeline of SPEARBench. III-A Data Preparation III-A 1 Dataset In this work, we use the dev and test sets of the Seamless Interaction dataset [ 1 ] , a collection of dyadic spoken conversations of up to 10 minutes each, designed to capture realistic human-human interaction. Both the improvised and naturalistic subsets of the corpus are used. The naturalistic subset contains prompted conversations carried out by non-actor participants and is intended to capture realistic everyday interaction patterns, while the improvised subset contains scenario-based interactions, and provides more controlled conversational situations designed to elicit particular roles or emotions, including a manual annotation of the interpersonal stances of the speakers, as well as their relationships. All conversations have been transcribed and diarized, and audio for each speaker is recorded on 2 different channels. Speakers include a range of ethnicities, accents, ages, and levels of education, as well as a gender balance close to parity. Table I shows the original size of the dev and test sets before and after dialogue selection. TABLE I : Number and hours of audios for the original conversations, and the selected dialogues. Improvised Naturalistic Total Dev Test Dev Test Original conversations 342 232 691 742 2007 Original hours 21.81h 15.84h 35.33h 40.82h 113.80h Selected dialogues 1165 994 1529 1731 5419 Contexts+Questions 4.78h 3.76h 6.76h 7.47h 22.77h Answers 2.67h 2.29h 5.23h 4.36h 14.56h Total selected hours 7.45h 6.05h 12.00h 11.83h 37.33h III-A 2 Dialogue selection A conversation from N N speakers { S n | n ∈ [ [ 1 , N ] ] } \\{S_{n}|n\\in[\\![1,N]\\!]\\} can be represented as a set of K K turns,We define one turn as a succession of utterances from a given speaker without interruption of backchannel over 0.5 seconds, so by definition, two consecutive turns are from different speakers. To extract one valid dialogue from a recorded conversation, we search for any set of K ≥ 3 K\\geq 3 consecutive turns from N = 2 N=2 speakers, whose second-to-last turn contains a question (transcription ends with a ’ ? ’). This creates three parts in any given valid dialogue: 1. Context : turns [ 1 , K − 2 ] [1,K-2] , show the previous exchanges in the conversation, from speakers { S 1 , S 2 } \\{S_{1},S_{2}\\} . 2. Question : turn K − 1 K-1 , shows an inquiry made by speaker S 1 S_{1} , which we know had an existing answer by a real speaker. The constraint imposed on the question is the simplest condition that ensures an answer. 3. Answer : turn K K , shows the human answer given by a speaker S 2 S_{2} , for later comparison to the evaluated models. This selection protocol identified at least one valid dialogue in 70.91% of the conversations, with an average of 4.6 valid dialogues extracted per conversation. Table I shows the size of the dev and test sets after dialogue selection. III-B LLM inference For each selected interaction, the evaluated model receives the context and question audio as input and is asked to produce a spoken answer. The benchmark stores two outputs for each inference: the generated answer waveform and the estimated start time of the answer. The start time is computed as the difference between the absolute time at which the model begins producing speech and the end of the context+question input. A positive value, therefore, indicates that the model waited until the end of the question before answering, while a negative value indicates that the model began answering before the input audio ended. Negative start times are treated as interruptions, since the model starts speaking before the human speaker has finished. We evaluate seven open-weights and proprietary S2S models with a range of model sizes and inference regimes, shown in Table II TABLE II : Models evaluated, with their inference mode, number of parameters when known, and Model Inference Open (# parameters when known) mode weights GPT-audio-1.5 [ 27 ] Non-streaming GPT-realtime-2 [ 28 ] Full-duplex Qwen3-Omni-30B-Instruct [ 49 ] (30B) Full-duplex ✓ \\checkmark Qwen2.5-Omni-7B [ 48 ] (7B) Half-duplex ✓ \\checkmark Gemini-2.5-flash-native-audio [ 11 ] Full-duplex Gemini-3.1-flash-live [ 19 ] Full-duplex Mini-omni [ 47 ] (0.5B) Half-duplex ✓ \\checkmark III-C Evaluation III-C 1 Intelligibility and Speech Quality We first include a small set of traditional metrics to facilitate comparison with existing work: intelligibility and speech quality . Intelligibility is measured through the relative success of Automatic Speech Recognition (ASR) systems. The transcripts of the answers are computed using a set of ASR systems ( whisper-large-v3 [ 31 ] , and qwen3-ASR-0.6B [ 35 ] ). For each answer, the WER and Character Error Rate (CER) are measured for each system’s outputs to assess the models’ intelligibility relative to human intelligibility in real-life scenarios, while reducing bias from a single evaluator. All the S2S models evaluated in this study provide a text version of their outputs upon inference, which are used as a reference to calculate WER. Speech Quality is measured through the Mean Opinion Score (MOS), automatically evaluated by the UTMOS model [ 34 ] . III-C 2 Interruptions and Latency Latency is defined as the time between the end of the question’s speech and the beginning of the voiced answer, measured using the Silero VAD [ 40 ] Voice Activity Detection model. Cases of interruption are not counted toward the latency, as they would theoretically have a negative latency. In this context, we define time of interruption as the total duration during which the model’s speech overlaps with the original speaker’s speech. If the time of interruption is not zero, one interruption is counted, being the total number of interruptions reported as well. III-C 3 Turn-Taking Naturalness We estimate turn-taking naturalness using predictive turn-taking models trained on natural dyadic conversations. Following the formulation of turn-taking naturalness as the predictive typicality of future voice activity in a two-speaker dialogue, we score each reconstructed interaction with the best evaluator model from [ 52 ] . This evaluator is based on the DualTurn-based model, which predicts future voice activity from the two-channel dialogue signal and assigns higher surprisal to less plausible local turn-taking patterns. For each model answer, we compute the turn-taking naturalness score for the answer given the context and the question, with both evaluator families, and average their outputs to reduce evaluator-specific bias. III-C 4 Language and Dialect Consistency Language is predicted using the MMS language identification system [ 30 ] , trained on 4,017 languages, providing up to 97.3% classification accuracy over 102 languages when evaluated on the FLEURS benchmark [ 12 ] . As Seamless Interaction is an English-only dataset, only the percentages of English and non-English answers are reported, as an answer in a different language, if not explicitly prompted, would be considered a failure. Dialect profile of the question and the answer is computed using Voxlect-English [ 15 ] , which shows a 83.0% accuracy over 16 English dialect categories: East Asia, English, Germanic, Irish, North America, Northern Irish, Oceania, Welsh, Romance, Scottish, Semitic, Slavic, South African, Southeast Asia, South Asia, and Others. Irish, Northern Irish, Scottish, English, and Welsh are merged into the ’ British Isles ’ category; ’ Others ’ is ignored. The resulting vector of 11 logits is used as a representation of the dialect profile. We use those dialect profiles to measure the dialectal entrainment as the least squares regression coefficient between the dialect of the question and the answer, and to measure the dialectal variance as the total variance (trace of the covariance matrix) of the dialect profiles. In this sense, an agent changing dialects during a conversation (measured through dialectal variance ) could be considered unnatural. In contrast, the dialectal entrainment metric provides information about the dialectal alignment between a speaker and the S2S model providing a response, which can be useful in many scenarios, but it is not always linked to naturalness, as a conversation between two speakers with different dialects can sound highly natural. III-C 5 Emotional Naturalness and Entrainement The emotional naturalness stage leverages the TRACE model [ 41 ] , which has shown a 97.01% accuracy to classify the naturalness of conversation based on their emotions on real and simulated datasets. For each pair of question and answer, embeddings are extracted using the Voxprofile Speech Emotion Recognition model [ 16 ] , as well as the Arousal, Valence and Dominance (AVD) of each utterance. Conversation context embeddings are extracted from the conversation prompts given to the participants, using the SBERT model all-MiniLM-L6-v2 [ 33 ] . Relationship embeddings are one-hot vectors computed from the relationships reported in the dataset. Emotion, context, and relationship embeddings are then input to the pre-trained emotional naturalness predictor [ 41 ] , which outputs an emotional naturalness score . In this study, values", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "84715e42-7455-4d7a-8298-ddf2e3500163", "uuid": "bd07f4c2-30b9-4037-83fa-6bd1cf5c8918", "timestamp": "2026-07-07T10:58:34.262Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": " ] . Natural conversation therefore requires not only intelligible speech, but also appropriate timing and turn-taking [ 8 ] : late responses may feel slow, while early responses may interrupt the user, especially in full-duplex systems that must decide when to answer while speech is still arriving [ 36 , 4 ] . Standard metrics such as WER and UTMOS [ 34 ] remain useful, but do not fully capture these interactional dimensions: a model can have low WER and high speech quality while answering at the wrong time, using a flat voice, missing the emotion of the question, or changing the interpersonal stance. Recent work has demonstrated that evaluator models can be used to reliably estimate conversation-level properties, including turn-taking naturalness with Voice Activity Prediction models [ 52 ] , emotional naturalness and entrainment [ 41 ] , interpersonal stance [ 45 ] , and dialect profiles across languages [ 15 ] . SPEARBench leverages these models in Section III-C . II-C Existing Benchmarks for Speech-to-Speech Language Models Evaluation Many benchmarks evaluate speech processing models and LLMs. Some focus on speech understanding tasks such as transcription, spoken question answering, speech translation, or audio reasoning, including SUPERB-style benchmarks for speech foundation models [ 51 ] . Others compare LLM abilities in text-only [ 24 , 7 ] or speech-based settings [ 50 , 53 , 38 ] . These benchmarks measure important capabilities, but they often focus on isolated utterances or task correctness rather than conversational behavior, leading to known gaps and inconsistencies across evaluations [ 23 ] . Recent work has begun evaluating full-duplex spoken interaction, including emergency scenarios [ 17 ] , latency [ 32 ] , interruptions [ 25 ] , and turn efficiency [ 17 ] . Some commercial initiatives, such as Artificial Analysis [ 5 ] , provide scores for AI agents that include automatic evaluation of pause handling, turn-taking, interruption handling, and backchannel handling, but they do not provide an open-source benchmark with peer-reviewed reports or articles. Other initiatives, such as Speech Arena [ 37 ] or Voice Arena [ 42 ] are more focused on text-to-speech systems rather than AI agents and mainly use human evaluations to create their leaderboards. Consequently, most benchmarks still focus on a single dimension, are not open, or require human intervention. SPEARBench complements them by providing an open-source automated benchmark for conversational naturalness on a wide set of aspects. Figure 1 : SPEARBench pipeline. III Methods This section details the proposed benchmark implementation, which consists of three steps: data preparation, LLM inference for each S2S model evaluated, and then evaluation. Figure 1 summarizes the pipeline of SPEARBench. III-A Data Preparation III-A 1 Dataset In this work, we use the dev and test sets of the Seamless Interaction dataset [ 1 ] , a collection of dyadic spoken conversations of up to 10 minutes each, designed to capture realistic human-human interaction. Both the improvised and naturalistic subsets of the corpus are used. The naturalistic subset contains prompted conversations carried out by non-actor participants and is intended to capture realistic everyday interaction patterns, while the improvised subset contains scenario-based interactions, and provides more controlled conversational situations designed to elicit particular roles or emotions, including a manual annotation of the interpersonal stances of the speakers, as well as their relationships. All conversations have been transcribed and diarized, and audio for each speaker is recorded on 2 different channels. Speakers include a range of ethnicities, accents, ages, and levels of education, as well as a gender balance close to parity. Table I shows the original size of the dev and test sets before and after dialogue selection. TABLE I : Number and hours of audios for the original conversations, and the selected dialogues. Improvised Naturalistic Total Dev Test Dev Test Original conversations 342 232 691 742 2007 Original hours 21.81h 15.84h 35.33h 40.82h 113.80h Selected dialogues 1165 994 1529 1731 5419 Contexts+Questions 4.78h 3.76h 6.76h 7.47h 22.77h Answers 2.67h 2.29h 5.23h 4.36h 14.56h Total selected hours 7.45h 6.05h 12.00h 11.83h 37.33h III-A 2 Dialogue selection A conversation from N N speakers { S n | n ∈ [ [ 1 , N ] ] } \\{S_{n}|n\\in[\\![1,N]\\!]\\} can be represented as a set of K K turns,We define one turn as a succession of utterances from a given speaker without interruption of backchannel over 0.5 seconds, so by definition, two consecutive turns are from different speakers. To extract one valid dialogue from a recorded conversation, we search for any set of K ≥ 3 K\\geq 3 consecutive turns from N = 2 N=2 speakers, whose second-to-last turn contains a question (transcription ends with a ’ ? ’). This creates three parts in any given valid dialogue: 1. Context : turns [ 1 , K − 2 ] [1,K-2] , show the previous exchanges in the conversation, from speakers { S 1 , S 2 } \\{S_{1},S_{2}\\} . 2. Question : turn K − 1 K-1 , shows an inquiry made by speaker S 1 S_{1} , which we know had an existing answer by a real speaker. The constraint imposed on the question is the simplest condition that ensures an answer. 3. Answer : turn K K , shows the human answer given by a speaker S 2 S_{2} , for later comparison to the evaluated models. This selection protocol identified at least one valid dialogue in 70.91% of the conversations, with an average of 4.6 valid dialogues extracted per conversation. Table I shows the size of the dev and test sets after dialogue selection. III-B LLM inference For each selected interaction, the evaluated model receives the context and question audio as input and is asked to produce a spoken answer. The benchmark stores two outputs for each inference: the generated answer waveform and the estimated start time of the answer. The start time is computed as the difference between the absolute time at which the model begins producing speech and the end of the context+question input. A positive value, therefore, indicates that the model waited until the end of the question before answering, while a negative value indicates that the model began answering before the input audio ended. Negative start times are treated as interruptions, since the model starts speaking before the human speaker has finished. We evaluate seven open-weights and proprietary S2S models with a range of model sizes and inference regimes, shown in Table II TABLE II : Models evaluated, with their inference mode, number of parameters when known, and Model Inference Open (# parameters when known) mode weights GPT-audio-1.5 [ 27 ] Non-streaming GPT-realtime-2 [ 28 ] Full-duplex Qwen3-Omni-30B-Instruct [ 49 ] (30B) Full-duplex ✓ \\checkmark Qwen2.5-Omni-7B [ 48 ] (7B) Half-duplex ✓ \\checkmark Gemini-2.5-flash-native-audio [ 11 ] Full-duplex Gemini-3.1-flash-live [ 19 ] Full-duplex Mini-omni [ 47 ] (0.5B) Half-duplex ✓ \\checkmark III-C Evaluation III-C 1 Intelligibility and Speech Quality We first include a small set of traditional metrics to facilitate comparison with existing work: intelligibility and speech quality . Intelligibility is measured through the relative success of Automatic Speech Recognition (ASR) systems. The transcripts of the answers are computed using a set of ASR systems ( whisper-large-v3 [ 31 ] , and qwen3-ASR-0.6B [ 35 ] ). For each answer, the WER and Character Error Rate (CER) are measured for each system’s outputs to assess the models’ intelligibility relative to human intelligibility in real-life scenarios, while reducing bias from a single evaluator. All the S2S models evaluated in this study provide a text version of their outputs upon inference, which are used as a reference to calculate WER. Speech Quality is measured through the Mean Opinion Score (MOS), automatically evaluated by the UTMOS model [ 34 ] . III-C 2 Interruptions and Latency Latency is defined as the time between the end of the question’s speech and the beginning of the voiced answer, measured using the Silero VAD [ 40 ] Voice Activity Detection model. Cases of interruption are not counted toward the latency, as they would theoretically have a negative latency. In this context, we define time of interruption as the total duration during which the model’s speech overlaps with the original speaker’s speech. If the time of interruption is not zero, one interruption is counted, being the total number of interruptions reported as well. III-C 3 Turn-Taking Naturalness We estimate turn-taking naturalness using predictive turn-taking models trained on natural dyadic conversations. Following the formulation of turn-taking naturalness as the predictive typicality of future voice activity in a two-speaker dialogue, we score each reconstructed interaction with the best evaluator model from [ 52 ] . This evaluator is based on the DualTurn-based model, which predicts future voice activity from the two-channel dialogue signal and assigns higher surprisal to less plausible local turn-taking patterns. For each model answer, we compute the turn-taking naturalness score for the answer given the context and the question, with both evaluator families, and average their outputs to reduce evaluator-specific bias. III-C 4 Language and Dialect Consistency Language is predicted using the MMS language identification system [ 30 ] , trained on 4,017 languages, providing up to 97.3% classification accuracy over 102 languages when evaluated on the FLEURS benchmark [ 12 ] . As Seamless Interaction is an English-only dataset, only the percentages of English and non-English answers are reported, as an answer in a different language, if not explicitly prompted, would be considered a failure. Dialect profile of the question and the answer is computed using Voxlect-English [ 15 ] , which shows a 83.0% accuracy over 16 English dialect categories: East Asia, English, Germanic, Irish, North America, Northern Irish, Oceania, Welsh, Romance, Scottish, Semitic, Slavic, South African, Southeast Asia, South Asia, and Others. Irish, Northern Irish, Scottish, English, and Welsh are merged into the ’ British Isles ’ category; ’ Others ’ is ignored. The resulting vector of 11 logits is used as a representation of the dialect profile. We use those dialect profiles to measure the dialectal entrainment as the least squares regression coefficient between the dialect of the question and the answer, and to measure the dialectal variance as the total variance (trace of the covariance matrix) of the dialect profiles. In this sense, an agent changing dialects during a conversation (measured through dialectal variance ) could be considered unnatural. In contrast, the dialectal entrainment metric provides information about the dialectal alignment between a speaker and the S2S model providing a response, which can be useful in many scenarios, but it is not always linked to naturalness, as a conversation between two speakers with different dialects can sound highly natural. III-C 5 Emotional Naturalness and Entrainement The emotional naturalness stage leverages the TRACE model [ 41 ] , which has shown a 97.01% accuracy to classify the naturalness of conversation based on their emotions on real and simulated datasets. For each pair of question and answer, embeddings are extracted using the Voxprofile Speech Emotion Recognition model [ 16 ] , as well as the Arousal, Valence and Dominance (AVD) of each utterance. Conversation context embeddings are extracted from the conversation prompts given to the participants, using the SBERT model all-MiniLM-L6-v2 [ 33 ] . Relationship embeddings are one-hot vectors computed from the relationships reported in the dataset. Emotion, context, and relationship embeddings are then input to the pre-trained emotional naturalness predictor [ 41 ] , which outputs an emotional naturalness score . In this study, values", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
